## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical understanding of combining UI state with asynchronous persistence, a common real-world pattern.

## Key Concepts
- Combine debouncing for UI-driven writes
- File I/O and JSON encoding in Swift
- SwiftUI data flow and @Published bindings
- Unit testing asynchronous code and filesystem writes

## Code Example
```swift
import Combine
import SwiftUI

class NotesStore: ObservableObject {
  @Published var note: String = ""
  private var cancellables = Set<AnyCancellable>()
  init() {
    $note
      .debounce(for: .milliseconds(500), scheduler: RunLoop.main)
      .sink { [weak self] text in
        self?.save(text)
      }
      .store(in: &cancellables)
  }
  func save(_ text: String) {
    let json = ["note": text]
    if let data = try? JSONSerialization.data(withJSONObject: json, options: []) {
      let url = FileManager.default.urls(for: .documentDirectory, in: .userDomainMask)[0]
        .appendingPathComponent("notes.json")
      try? data.write(to: url)
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test cancellation of a pending save when the app moves to background?
- How would you extend to multi-note scenarios with conflict resolution?

