## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design simple, observable UI with a practical persistence pattern.

## Key Concepts
- SwiftUI TextEditor binding
- Debounce using DispatchWorkItem
- UserDefaults persistence
- Lightweight unit testing of async behavior

## Code Example
```javascript
// Swift-like pseudocode demonstrating debounce autosave
class NoteViewModel: ObservableObject {
  @Published var text = ""
  private var workItem: DispatchWorkItem?
  func textChanged(_ newValue: String) {
    text = newValue
    workItem?.cancel()
    let item = DispatchWorkItem { self.saveDraft() }
    workItem = item
    DispatchQueue.main.asyncAfter(deadline: .now() + 1.0, execute: item)
  }
  func saveDraft() {
    UserDefaults.standard.set(text, forKey: "noteDraft")
  }
  func loadDraft() {
    text = UserDefaults.standard.string(forKey: "noteDraft") ?? ""
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you extend to support multiple notes?  
- How would you ensure autosave runs if the app goes to background?  
- How would you test the debounce logic more deterministically?

